      <h1>Medicines Info</h1>
    <h2>Caring for your child with chickenpox</h2>
	<h3>Medicines (ask your pharmacist)</h3>
	<ul>
	  <li>Use children's <a href="#" data-bind="click:getDataAndBind">paracetamol</a> to bring down your child's temperature. Don't exceed the recommended dose.</li>
	  <li>Never give aspirin to children under 16.</li>
	  <li>There is a small risk of <a href="#" data-bind="click:getDataAndBind" >ibuprofen</a> causing skin complications during chickenpox.</li>
	  <li>Calamine lotion, emollients or cooling gels can soothe and comfort the skin.</li>
	  <li><a href="#">Antihistamines</a>, such as chlorphenamine, can be given at bedtime to ease itching and will help your child sleep. These shouldn't be used for children under one (unless prescribed).</li>
	</ul>

